{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596205"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:11:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:11:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15398"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15398","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15398"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63578"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8089"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15398"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49032"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20854"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63578"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man presents with a two day history of worsening lower abdominal pain and fever. He is normally in good health and this is the first time he has experienced these symptoms. On examination his pulse is 90/min, blood pressure 128/80 mmHg and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. The only abnormal finding on abdominal examination is some mild tenderness in the left iliac fossa. A CT scan is performed with shows a 10cm long area of thickening of the sigmoid colon with a 3 cm pericolic abscess. No other abnormalities are found.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Modified Hinchey classification is used to grade the severity of diverticulitis based on clinical, radiological, and operative findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following stages represents this patient\u0027s grade of diverticulitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0","1","II","III","IV"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Modified Hinchey classification for diverticulitis has the following stages:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0\u003C/strong\u003E: Mild clinical diverticulitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1a\u003C/strong\u003E: Pericolic inflammation only\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIb\u003C/strong\u003E: Confined pericolic inflammation with pericolic or mesenteric abscess\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EII\u003C/strong\u003E: Pelvic, distant intra-abdominal, or retroperitoneal abscess\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIII\u003C/strong\u003E: Generalised purulent peritonitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIV\u003C/strong\u003E: Generalised faecal peritonitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has Stage Ib diverticulitis. He is reasonably well, with few abdominal signs and a low grade fever. The CT shows some pericolic inflammation and a small pericolic abscess. The Modified Hinchey classification helps guide management decisions, with stages 0 and Ia typically managed conservatively, while stages Ib through IV often some form of intervention. Depending on the size of the abscess, it might need to be drained (percutaneously) or require a surgical approach.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Modified Hinchey classification describes the severity of diverticulitis from stage 0 (mild) to stage IV (faecal peritonitis)"],"references":["Piscopo N, Ellul P. Diverticular Disease: A Review on Pathophysiology and Recent Evidence. Ulster Med J. 2020 Sep;89(2):83-88. Epub 2020 Oct 21. PMID: 33093692; PMCID: PMC7576390","Feuerstein JD, Falchuk KR. Diverticulosis and Diverticulitis. Mayo Clin Proc. 2016 Aug;91(8):1094-104. doi: 10.1016/j.mayocp.2016.03.012. Epub 2016 May 5. PMID: 27156370","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49032"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15398"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49032"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T17:43:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T17:44:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8089"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63578"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"descript